caption.text: Fare evasion is spiking on New York City buses, and with the MTA facing a financial crisis, people not paying for a ride every day could end up having a major impact. Click the LINK IN BIO to watch the full story and find out how the MTA is planning to fight the problem.

caption.text: New York City’s 2022 @rockefellercenter Christmas Tree will be crowned with a 900-pound Swarovski star for its debut and lighting on Wednesday, November 30. caption.text: A New York-bound Delta flight was forced to make an emergency landing after flames were spotted coming out of one of the plane’s wings. According to The Glasgow Times, the flight from Edinburgh, Scotland, to New York’s JFK Airport made the emergency landing in Glasgow shortly after takeoff. Visit the LINK IN BIO to read the passengers’ reactions on board.

caption.text:
ZEPPELIN TAKE NEW YORK - 49 years since Led Zeppelin blew the doors off of New York’s Madison Square Garden. Here, the band can be seen in the midst of of “Dazed and Confused” with Jimmy Page playing a cool little start/stop section that the fans are surely appreciating. Zeppelin came out with such a high-level of energy for these shows and it’s pretty remarkable for a band that was just wrapping up a massive two-leg tour. They performed for three straight nights at MSG, which were professionally filmed for the concert film “The Song Remains The Same.” 

1973 was a big year for Zeppelin. Just 2 months prior to these New York shows, they played to 56,800 fans in Tampa, breaking The Beatles record for an audience set at Shea Stadium in 1965. At this point, it really seemed like Zeppelin had few battles they hadn’t won. To Jimmy Page, the lead guitarist and architect of the band, it was Zep’s time to shine. “By 1973 we really had confidence,” Page told Brad Tolinski in Light and Shade (2013). “By then we were not only able to play but also project with it.” With the huge momentum the band was riding, Page got caught up in this and didn’t sleep for FIVE nights during these MSG shows. Page tried to break down what it was like leaving an arena full of adrenaline like he was in New York at the end of that ’73 tour. He said he couldn’t have slept if he tried. So he basically stopped trying. “We were in New York, we were making a movie and playing great shows,” Page said. “It was difficult to shut down that kind of electricity. You’d try to go to bed, but most of the time you gave up, because it was more fun to go out and enjoy yourself.” Enjoy

caption.text:
#WATCH - A parking building collapse in New York City has been described as feeling “like an earthquake”. 

At least one person is dead, and multiple others are injured after concrete floors fell on top of each other “like a stack of pancakes” in Lower Manhattan’s financial district. 

Video of the aftermath shows cars hanging in between floors of the three-story building. 

☝️ Head to the link in bio for more on this story. 

#1newsnz #newyork #manhattan #buildingcollapse
